  "prompt": "How do jellyfish breath?",
  "response": "Jellyfish breathe through a process called **diffusion**, as they lack specialized respiratory organs like lungs or gills. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Body Structure:** Jellyfish have a gelatinous, mostly water-based body that is typically transparent and very thin. This thinness maximizes their surface area relative to their volume, facilitating efficient gas exchange.\n\n2. **Gas Exchange:** \n   - **Oxygen Intake:** Oxygen dissolved in the surrounding seawater diffuses directly across the jellyfish\u2019s outer skin (ectoderm) into their cells.\n   - **Carbon Dioxide Release:** Similarly, carbon dioxide produced by their cellular metabolism diffuses out from their cells back into the surrounding water.\n\n3. **Movement and Water Flow:** Some jellyfish actively pump water through their bodies by contracting their bell (the main body part) to help circulate water, enhancing the rate of diffusion and ensuring a consistent supply of oxygen while removing carbon dioxide.\n\n4. **Efficiency:** The simple body plan and high water content allow jellyfish to efficiently manage their respiratory needs without the complexity of specialized organs. This method is well-suited to their often passive lifestyle, where they drift with ocean currents.\n\nIn summary, jellyfish rely on their permeable, thin bodies to facilitate the passive exchange of gases directly with the surrounding water, enabling them to breathe effectively in their aquatic environment.",
